Mapping ACPI Thermal Zones to Physical Sensors on Modern Microsoft Surface Devices
Executive summary
A truly definitive, SKU-by-SKU mapping of Windows-visible ACPI Thermal Zone instance IDs (for example, TZ01_0, TZ02_0) to physical sensors (CPU/GPU/battery/skin/charger/etc.) is only possible when the firmware’s ACPI tables contain unambiguous identifiers (for example, an ACPI _STR description such as “Primary Battery” or “GPU”) and when those ThermalZone objects can be independently tied to a known sensor interface. In practice, Microsoft Surface firmware varies significantly by generation and platform:

Some Surface devices expose ThermalZone objects whose _STR fields are human-readable sensor labels like “Primary Battery”, “GPU”, “SSD Temp”, “SOC Temp”, and “Tskin …”. This enables high-confidence mappings directly from the disassembled ACPI tables. A clear example is Surface Pro 7, whose DSDT contains several ThermalZone objects with descriptive _STR values. 

Other Surface devices expose ThermalZone objects whose _STR values are opaque codes such as RTS1…RTS8 and VTS1…VTS3 (observed on Surface Pro 8). Without additional proprietary documentation or measurement correlation, these cannot be mapped conclusively to “CPU vs skin vs charger” at the per-zone level. 

Microsoft Surface devices also increasingly rely on the Surface System Aggregator Module (SSAM) / embedded controller. Linux gained a dedicated driver (surface_temp) to read out temperature probes connected via the Surface Aggregator Module, reinforcing that many Surface temperature channels are EC/SSAM-backed rather than “classic” ACPI-only sensors. 

This report provides:

A device-by-device, evidence-backed mapping where the ACPI tables are explicit (high confidence).
A device-by-device identification of where the ThermalZone objects exist and what they are called when the firmware uses opaque naming, along with exactly what additional data is needed to complete the mapping.
Scope note: Microsoft Surface is a large family (2016–2026 includes dozens of models and multiple CPU-platform variants). The most comprehensive public, primary dataset of Surface ACPI tables I found is the linux-surface acpidumps repository, which contains ACPI table disassemblies for many Surface devices and variants (Intel vs AMD vs Qualcomm). 

