Primary evidence is taken from disassembled ACPI tables (DSDT/SSDT) in linux-surface/acpidumps (firmware-derived). 

Interpretation is augmented by Linux kernel Surface Aggregator documentation and the surface_temp driver patchset, which explicitly targets thermal sensors routed through the Surface Aggregator Module. 

Where naming is opaque, the linux-surface community explicitly notes that newer generations may require Windows driver reverse engineering or other mapping discovery beyond ACPI strings. 

ACPI evidence types used in this report
ACPI/DSDT/SSDT excerpt (primary): A ThermalZone object (e.g., ThermalZone (TZ07)) with _STR and _TMP is direct evidence of what the firmware calls the thermal channel and how temperature is obtained. (Example: Surface Pro 7 DSDT zone list.) 

Kernel driver mapping (primary/secondary): The Linux surface_temp driver and Surface Aggregator documentation describe how Surface devices expose thermal sensors via SSAM/EC. This supports interpreting _TMP calls that appear to be SAM/SSAM-backed. 

Community reverse-engineering status (supporting): The surface-aggregator-module issue discussion explains that on some newer devices thermal ID strings are not easily mapped and may be encoded in Windows drivers. 

