Devices with ACPI thermal zones present but not conclusively mappable from public primary sources
This section lists modern Microsoft devices where ACPI ThermalZone objects are clearly defined, but the zone-to-physical-sensor mapping is not derivable to your requested granularity because identifiers are opaque and Microsoft does not publish a complete mapping.

Surface Pro 8
Where the thermal zones are defined: in a Microsoft OEM SSDT (OEM Table ID "SsdtSurf"). 

ACPI ThermalZone objects found: TZ01–TZ08 plus TZ09, TZ0A, TZ0B where _STR values are RTS1…RTS8 and VTS1…VTS3. 

What can be stated definitively (and what cannot):

Definitive: the firmware exposes multiple thermal zones and names them (for humans/OS) with short codes RTS* and VTS*. 
Not definitive from public ACPI alone: whether RTS1 is CPU, GPU, battery, skin, charger, etc.
This uncertainty is consistent with linux-surface’s own assessment: for newer generations, the older approach of “ID strings embedded in ACPI indicate what it is used for” may not hold, and mapping might require reverse engineering the Windows driver or other additional data. 

Provisional classification (not the “definitive mapping” you requested):

RTS* and VTS* are likely internal temperature probes used by the Surface thermal/telemetry stack, but categorising them as CPU vs skin vs charger without further evidence would be speculative. 
Additional data required to complete a definitive mapping:

A Windows-side trace or reverse engineering result showing which physical component each RTS* / VTS* corresponds to (linux-surface explicitly flags this possibility). 
Empirical correlation: controlled workload tests (CPU-only, GPU-only, charging-only, SSD stress) while logging zone temperatures to see which channels respond, combined with physical probing (IR camera/thermocouples). This would constitute “measurement” evidence.
Cross-correlation with SSAM thermal sensor names returned via the surface_temp interface (Linux), if the returned labels are more descriptive than ACPI _STR. The existence of a dedicated surface_temp driver indicates that such sensor enumeration and naming exists in the SSAM protocol. 
Full model inventory and what is still needed for a complete 2016–2026 device-by-device mapping
Inventory of Microsoft devices with public ACPI dumps in scope
The linux-surface acpidumps repository enumerates ACPI table sets for many Microsoft devices and variants, including (among others) Surface Book/Go/Laptop/Pro lines and Windows Dev Kit 2023. 

From the repository listing visible via GitHub, the following modern device directories (among others) exist and are relevant to your requested “since 2016” scope (some pre-2016 directories also exist): Surface Book 2/3; Surface Go 1–4; Surface Laptop 1–6 and Laptop 7 (Qualcomm); Surface Laptop Go 1–3; Surface Laptop SE; Surface Laptop Studio 1–2; Surface Pro 5–9 plus Pro X variants; Surface Studio 2; Windows Dev Kit 2023. 

Why “all devices since 2016” is not yet fully satisfiable from public primary sources alone
Even with ACPI table disassemblies available, not all firmware encodes sensor identity in human-readable form. The Surface ecosystem increasingly routes thermal sensing through the Surface Aggregator Module (SSAM). Linux-side work explicitly targets these “newer Surface devices” and treats thermal sensors as a SAM/EC subsystem. 

Furthermore, the linux-surface community explicitly notes that on newer generations the “ID string embedded in ACPI” approach may not be present and that mappings could be encoded in Windows drivers, implying that ACPI-only extraction may be insufficient. 

Where to obtain ACPI/DSDT/firmware for devices not conclusively mapped here
If you need a definitive mapping for each model and SKU, for each target device you will typically need:

ACPI tables from the device (primary)

Linux runtime tables: /sys/firmware/acpi/tables/ (includes DSDT and SSDT*), or an ACPI table dump via acpidump. (These are standard kernel/OS mechanisms; the exact method depends on OS and privileges.)
Public community collection: the linux-surface/acpidumps repository contains a large set of device-specific dumps and is the best single known public index for Surface ACPI tables. 
Surface Aggregator / SSAM thermal sensor interface (primary-to-secondary)

Linux kernel Surface Aggregator documentation describes the client/driver model and provides context for how Surface EC-exposed subsystems (including thermal) are addressed. 
The surface_temp driver (and its patch history) documents that thermal probes exist behind SSAM and can be enumerated and named (even if those names are short/opaque on some devices). 
When the ACPI _STR is opaque (e.g., RTS1), you will need at least one of:

A Windows driver reverse engineering result mapping IDs → physical sensors (linux-surface identifies this as potentially necessary). 
Measurement correlation logs linking each zone to a physical heat source/workload.
Key takeaways
Surface Pro 7 and Surface Book 2 provide high-confidence, device-specific mappings because their ACPI ThermalZone _STR fields directly identify the sensor target (“Primary Battery”, “GPU”, “SSD Temp”, “SOC Temp”, “Tskin…”, “dGPU”, “Base battery”). 

Surface Pro 8 demonstrates the main blocker to a universal “definitive mapping”: ThermalZone _STR identifiers can be opaque (RTS*, VTS*), and public primary sources may not contain the requisite semantic mapping. This limitation is explicitly recognised by the linux-surface reverse-engineering community. 

The Surface thermal stack is strongly tied to the Surface System Aggregator Module (SSAM) in newer devices. Any serious attempt to complete the mapping across all Surface models should combine ACPI parsing with SSAM driver-level evidence (Linux) and/or Windows driver analysis and empirical measurement. 
